{
  "query": "What are the benefits and drawbacks of managing water levels and features like ditches and ponds on farmland to enhance biodiversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Benefits: Raising water levels in ditches or grassland was associated with increased bird numbers, breeding bird numbers, plant species that favour wet conditions, and invertebrate numbers or biomass in agricultural landscapes (Action 121). Managing ditches to benefit wildlife showed that some farmland birds responded positively to the presence of ditches managed for wildlife, with bunded ditches visited by more birds than non-bunded ditches (Action 180). Maintaining traditional water meadows resulted in increased population sizes or territories of northern lapwing, common redshank and black-tailed godwit and increased plant species richness (Action 696).\n\nDrawbacks: Raising water levels resulted in a net loss of plant species in one study and did not affect lapwing foraging rate, while another study found common snipe declined on sites under management to maintain water meadows (Actions 121, 696). Some farmland bird species did not respond positively or responded negatively to ditch management (Action 180). Studies found that managing traditional water meadows by grazing had mixed impacts on wildlife and the productivity of northern lapwings was too low to sustain populations on three of the four water meadows managed for waders (Action 696).",
